Expectations in San Antonio are high every year; it's a trivial price to pay for well nearly two decades of sustained success. Most Spurs fans have staked their tents firmly in the "championship or bust" camp, and it appears Vegas has joined.
At 4/1, the Spurs have the second-best odds to win the NBA championship, trailing only LeBron's Cavaliers (2/1), who mocked the the luxury tax threshold this summer by spending hundreds of millions to keep the King in a position to compete for a crown. A team generally expected to, at the least, make it to the NBA Finals, should also be the prohibitive favorite to capture the Western Conference title. The Warriors (3/1) won't sink so easily, though. The young team by the Bay is looking to establish a dynasty of its own, and they'll likely have to go through San Antonio to do so. There's a reason why Nikola Milutinov is the darkest of horses in the Rookie of the Year race: the 20-year-old Serbian isn't even on the Spurs' roster. San Antonio's 2015 first-round pick is stashed overseas, playing for European power Olympiacos.
These odds will eventually be updated, and though Brobdingnagian Croatian rookie Boban Marjanovic could sneak his way onto the bottom rungs of the list, you'd be better off spending your money on almost anything else. Bet: Rookie of the Year Odds: Nikola Milutinov +20500 Source: 5Dimes

Leonard is 24, but his list of accomplishments already reads like that of a hoops legend: NBA Champion, NBA Finals MVP, Defensive Player of the Year. There are just two items missing from his enviable collection of accolades and awards: All-Star selection and regular-season MVP.
If the Spurs approach the 70-win threshold and Leonard can sniff 20 points per game, he'll garner recognition, though splitting votes with the more offensively-minded Aldridge could diminish his chances. Since the 1999-2000 season, the lowest points per game average to capture a scoring title was 27.71 by Kevin Durant. No Spur has averaged more than 22 a game over the past decade.
Aldridge has seen his scoring average jump from 21.1 to 23.4 over the past three seasons, but that increase hasn't been enough to crack even the top-five.
The "Spurs Way" isn't built on the back of prolific bucket-getters, rather, it's built on decisive ball movement and singular imagination. The men above Aldridge, including Kevin Durant at +250, all play in systems more tailored to individual offensive greatness. Bet : Scoring champion Odds : LaMarcus Aldridge +3300 Source : 888sport

The gray may be sneaking into the hair sprouting from his temples and chin, but the defensive stylings of Tim Duncan have yet to fade.
Last year, at age 38, Duncan averaged 2.0 blocks, the highest mark for a player in their age-38 season. Duncan doesn't have the mobility or agility of his youth, but his dexterity and instinct remain two of the sharpest tools in the game. Bet : Blocks leader Odds : Tim Duncan +3300 Source : 888sports

Texas stocks the bettor with the Spurs, Rockets and Mavericks, while California represents the defending-champion Warriors, the lowly kings, the fallen Lakers and the Chris Paul-led Clippers.
The Mavericks, Lakers and Kings are essentially inconsequential throw-ins that just so happen to reside in a state with true contenders. The money here is on the Spurs-Rockets and Warriors-Clippers to emerge.

Image 40 of 40 Spurs won’t win NBA championship, league GMs say 1 / 40 Back to Gallery The Spurs had their fingerprints all over several categories in the NBA's annual GM survey, released Tuesday. "Team Most Likely To Win the Championship" was not one of them.
In the survey, produced by NBA.com, league general managers select Kawhi Leonard as the NBA's top defender, tab LaMarcus Aldridge as the most impactful free agent acquisition and Gregg Popovich as the league's top coach.
They pick the Cleveland Cavaliers to win their first-ever championship. The Spurs were the second-most popular choice, polling at 25 percent to the Cavs' 53.6 percent.
In other results, the Spurs were the overwhelming choice as the team that made the best offseason moves, notably adding Aldridge and David West. West finished with Ty Lawson (Houston) and Paul Pierce (L.A. Clippers) as the most underrated offseason signing.
